<TEXT>
james traficant jr an ohio congressman 
waging an onagain offagain campaign for president is hoping to 
pick up a few delegates today in his home state but admits his 
chances of winning even his own congressional district are slim 
traficant a democrat from suburban youngstown who also is 
seeking his third term in congress announced last summer that he 
would run for president to attract attention to the problems of his 
congressional district which has been hard hit by the decline of 
the steel industry 
traficant said he would run a national campaign for the 
democratic presidential nomination but it never materialized he 
blamed a lack of money 
if i had the same amount of money these other candidates had 
in the state of ohio and could have come on tv the past two weeks 
there would have been a fight he said 
leesa brown of the ohio secretary of states office said 
traficant met the qualifications to get onto the ballot in 12 of 
ohios 21 congressional districts 
a former sheriff traficant is best known for successfully 
defending himself against charges that he accepted 163000 from 
mobsters in 1980 but he had little name recognition outside his 
own district 
william binning chairman of the political science department at 
youngstown state university said traficants presidential 
candidacy was actually given some credence early on because so many 
of the democratic candidates were not well known nationally 
but ultimately binning said i think traficant would have to 
win a major statewide office in ohio in order to be considered a 
viable candidate for president 
a survey conducted by youngstown states center for urban 
studies suggested residents of his district favor traficant as a 
congressman but not as a presidential candidate 
the poll commissioned by the youngstown vindicator indicated 
38 percent of the 697 people surveyed favor michael dukakis the 
democratic frontrunner with traficant supported by 14 percent and 
jesse jackson backed by 11 percent nearly a quarter of the 
participants were undecided 
however more than 70 percent of the same respondents supported 
traficants bid to a third term in congress 
the poll was conducted between april 11 and april 20 and had a 
margin of error of 56 percentage points 
