<DOCNO> AP880503-0040 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
researchers seeking to cure crippling 
diseases like arthritis and multiple sclerosis in humans say 
theyve taken an early important step by isolating the gene that 
causes a form of arthritis in mice 
we are on the way to finding the cure for this type of 
arthritis in mice tariq m haqqi a molecular biologist at the 
mayo clinic in rochester minn said monday 
if the same kinds of arthritiscausing genes or inherited 
blueprints can be identified in humans we are one step closer 
to the cure and prevention of human rheumatoid arthritis and other 
human autoimmune diseases in which the body apparently is 
attacked by its own diseasefighting immune system haqqi said 
discovery of the gene vb6 that causes mouse arthritis was 
outlined by haqqi during the annual meeting of the federation of 
american societies for experimental biology which drew 22000 
scientists and exhibitors 
the discovery is very exciting because it is the first time 
scientists have isolated a gene that causes arthritis said dr c 
garrison fathman an immunologistrheumatologist at stanford 
university 
but he said it still will take scientists years to find a cure 
for rheumatoid arthritis which afflicts 7 million americans or 
any of the other 100 forms of arthritis and related diseases such 
as lupus multiple sclerosis and juvenile or insulindependent 
diabetes 
fathman recently used what are called monoclonal antibodies 
proteins made in the laboratory to target specific types of cells 
to attack t cells a type of white blood cell in the immune system 
that cause diabetes in mice the mice were cured he reported 
friday in the journal science 
haqqi is now trying to cure mice of arthritis by using other 
tailormade monoclonal antibodies to attack the t cells responsible 
for that disease without harming other white blood cells which are 
needed to defend the body against infection 
t cells normally help fight infection by recognizing an invading 
germ or foreign substance and then triggering production of 
antibodies to combat them but bacterial and viral infections also 
can trigger autoimmune diseases 
haqqi and his colleagues identified and isolated the gene that 
codes for production of a certain receptor on the surface of t 
cells in mice 
haqqi said this receptor causes the t cells to lose their 
ability to distinguish foreign collagen or connective tissue from 
the collagen naturally found in cartilage tendon and skin 
so the t cells attack collagen in cartilage in the mices 
joints causing the inflammation swelling and pain known as 
arthritis 
scientists from the howard hughes medical institute at 
washington university in st louis and from the university of 
tennessee in memphis also worked on the study in which mice 
developed arthritis when injected with collagen from cows the 
disease is similar to crippling rheumatoid arthritis in humans 
if researchers can identify the genes for human t cell receptors 
that go awry to cause human arthritis and other autoimmune 
diseases then we can cure the disease and prevent it by 
producing monoclonal antibodies to attack the culprit t cells while 
leaving other white blood cells unharmed haqqi said 
but he cautioned the antibody that works in mice may not 
work in humans so well have to find the antibody that works in 
humans 
fathman agreed saying different monoclonal antibodies would be 
needed not only for every form of arthritis and autoimmune 
disease but possibly for each individual human 
</TEXT>
