<TEXT>
south africa cuba and angola today began 
ussponsored negotiations aimed at the withdrawal of foreign 
troops from the civil war in angola the us embassy said 
the embassy said the scheduled twoday talks had begun but 
refused to disclose where representatives are meeting in london 
the british foreign office said the nations also would discuss 
independence for southwest africa or namibia which south africa 
controls 
the talks come after an eightyear us effort to secure the 
withdrawal of 40000 cuban troops sent in 1975 to defend angolas 
marxist government against prowestern rebels 
chester crocker us assistant secretary of state for african 
affairs led the american delegation to the negotiations 
cuba was to be represented by its foreign minister raul roa 
kouri and angolas foreign minister alfonso van dunem also was 
to attend 
south africa sent a delegation headed by a neil van heerden 
director general of the department of foreign affairs 
crocker made no comment before the talks they were announced on 
friday in a brief british statement after crocker conferred in 
london with soviet deputy foreign minister anatoly adamishin 
adamishin told a news conference on friday that moscow supported 
the political dynamism behind the talks 
south african troops are in angola to attack bases of the south 
west africa peoples organization which seeks independence for 
southwest africa and to support the angolan rebels known as the 
national union for the total independence of angola 
south africa acknowledges up to 3000 troops in southern angola 
while angola says there are 9000 south africans there backed by 
heavy artillery 
in return for a cuban withdrawal angola and the soviet union 
want south africa to give namibia independence as demanded in a 
1966 un resolution 
the british foreign office said the talks will cover both the 
troop withdrawals and independence for namibia 
but the exclusion of namibian and angolan rebels appeared to 
indicate the emphasis will be on getting the south africans and 
cubans out of angola rather than namibian independence 
previous attempts at settlement have foundered partly on the 
reagan administrations demand that cuban troops leave before 
namibia becomes independent president pw botha of south africa 
repeated that demand in johannesburg on monday 
in recent months the south africans and cubans have been bogged 
down in heavy fighting around the strategic southeastern city of 
cuito cuanavale 
the war is a heavy burden on the already strapped angolan 
economy and the cubans have sustained high but undisclosed 
losses 
south africa acknowledges that more than 50 of its troops have 
been killed in angola since september 
