protectionism as an example for other countries 
in defending free trade and resisting protectionist pressures 
this reagan administration has shown responsibility that deserves 
recognition overseas holkeri said in an address prepared for a 
national press club audience 
he also wished reagan the very best for the moscow summit at 
the end of may holkeri who met the president monday said reagan 
during his planned presummit stopover in finland will get a warm 
welcome from a friendly people who cherish good relations with the 
united states 
the prime minister who is making a weeklong visit to the 
united states said the worst scenario would be a trade war 
between the major trading powers avoiding trade confrontation 
is now a high priority for all governments 
in remarks that could be interpreted as criticism of some 
provisions of the trade bill reagan plans to veto holkeri urged 
priority for the multilateral approach to trade over nationalist 
economic policies 
it is crucial that all countries refrain from new 
protectionist measures and observe 1986 commitments at the start 
of the uruguay round of global trade talks for a freeze on existing 
levels of protection he said 
successful conclusion of the round by the end of 1990 demands 
constructive actions by all countries regardless of size and and 
puts a heavy responsibility on key players in world trade such 
as the united states he said 
we should discard support for ailing industries he said if 
buy american policies are acceptable why not buy finnish 
he asked he said absence of subsidies for industry forces finnish 
factories to become competitive and stay competitive 
holkeri a banker who a year ago became head of finlands first 
conservativeled coalition government with the social democrats 
said his country believes in the free market and wants to cooperate 
with the united states in promoting multilateralism in trade 
