<TEXT>
congress should pass a universal health 
insurance plan similar to the one signed into law last month by 
massachusetts gov michael dukakis former cabinet member joseph 
califano said tuesday 
califano who was secretary of health education and welfare 
during the carter administration said all other industrialized 
nations make health care or insurance available to their citizens 
he said his son is working and studying at a west german 
hospital and receives full health coverage for 45 a month 
we can do it in this country the dukakis plan provides a 
model califano told the joint economic committees subcommittee 
on education and health at a hearing on the future of health care 
in america 
the plan advanced by dukakis the likely democratic presidential 
nominee gives tax incentives to employers who offer health 
insurance to their employees and sets up a state fund to help the 
unemployed the selfemployed and others buy insurance for 
themselves at subsidized rates the cost is estimated at 645 
million over the next five years 
universal health insurance was one of three changes which 
califano said he would make if he were trying to improve us 
health care and had no limits on what he could spend 
he said he would also mount a huge health education and disease 
prevention campaign and spend an enormous amount of money on 
research into addiction and the afflictions of the aged 
particularly incontinence immobility and memory loss 
califano said at least 1 billion a year should be spent on 
aging research and a new institute on addiction should be created 
at the national institutes of health to study all forms of 
substance abuse including smoking 
the cost of addiction in health care alone easily exceeds 50 
billion yet out of a total health research budget of 6 billion 
the government spends less than 200 million to learn about 
addiction said califano 
califano also offered ways to hold down health care costs among 
them capping malpractice awards and setting treatment standards 
based on what is proven to work the latter would help reduce 
unnecessary procedures and hospital admissions he said 
authorities also need a sea change in community attitudes to 
help them start eliminating 400000 excess hospital beds that are 
costing 12 billion a year to maintain califano said 
closing hospitals is hard labor califano acknowledged 
everyone admits we have too many hospital beds in america 
theyre just all in someone elses town city or neighborhood 
califano author of a 1986 book called americas health care 
revolution said the major stumbling block to his recommendations 
is the health care industry 
for these efforts to succeed to have any hope of restraining 
costs the political system has to free itself from domination by 
health care providers califano said he said their political 
action committees spent more on congressional races in the last 
election cycle than any other industry except financial services 
daniel waldo of the governments health care financing 
administration said the trend toward higher spending on health 
care is inevitable and desirable he said more and more money is 
becoming available for health care as national income increases 
the aging of the population also contributes to higher 
expenditures he said as does the willingness of people to pay for 
more care demonstrated by the rise in adult orthodontia 
