<TEXT>
federal officials on wednesday will kick off 
an intensive threeweek campaign to alert americans about aids 
focused around the mailing of a pamphlet on the deadly disease to 
every household in the nation 
health and human services secretary otis r bowen surgeon 
general c everett koop and other top administration health leaders 
scheduled a news conference to officially unveil the booklet whose 
contents were being kept secret tuesday 
the promotional campaign including television spots and 
posters in each of the nations post offices is designed to alert 
americans to be looking for the historic pamphlet when it starts 
showing up in mailboxes may 26 
it will be the first time the us government has sent a health 
advisory directly to every american with a mailing address 
the secrecy surrounding the actual content of the document stems 
from decision by department officials to apply a strict reading to 
congressional directions ordering that a national mailing be 
undertaken by june 30 
that language in the omnibus budget bill covering the current 
fiscal year said the mailing was to be prepared and distributed 
without necessary clearance of the content by any official 
organization or office 
although health department officials have been wary of 
discussing preparation of the document they have acknowledged that 
they interpreted the wording to mean that the pamphlets content 
should not be subject to prior scrutiny either by the white house 
or congress itself 
congress called for a similar mailing last year but with less 
explicit language that project was never completed in part 
because of objections raised by some white house officials 
one of the reasons given was that because president reagan had 
just appointed a white house aids commission to make 
recommendations on overall aids policy it would be appropriate for 
the panel to review any mailing 
however the commission did not get into the issue at the time 
on grounds that it was just beginning its work and was not ready to 
examine specific inititives the panel was not asked to review the 
current mailing and did not ask to be involved 
the commission has not formally or informally been involved in 
the planning or preparation or writing of this booklet spokesman 
tom brandt said tuesday in an interview 
he said retired navy adm james watkins and the panels 
executive director are familiar with some elements of it but 
like everybody else in town they are waiting to see it and hope it 
is successful 
aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a contagious 
incurable isease that attacks the bodys immune system rendering 
it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections the virus 
most often is spread through close contact with blood blood 
products or semen from infected persons 
the diseases chief victims have been homosexual men and 
intravenous drug users with a small percentage of cases attributed 
to transfusions of contaminated blood heterosexual contact and 
spread from infected pregnant women to their offspring 
as of april 21 aids had been diagnosed in about 59500 
americans of whom more than half or about 33000 have died since 
june 1981 according to the cdc 
hhs spokesman chuck kline said the pamphlet will be as 
complete as it can be within a relatively constrained format 
discussing aids in terms of how you can get aids how you cant get 
aids the various precautions that can be taken beginning of 
course with avoiding risky behavior 
he said there are sections on aids and children aids and 
dating babies with aids and on people with aids and the rights 
they have and the obligations owed to them 
asked specifically whether it will mention condoms kline said 
this particular mailer addresses all aspects of aids and how it 
is communicated and how one can avoid or if not avoid at least 
provide the best protection for the circumstances 
since 1986 when he issued a 36page surgeon generals report on 
aids koop has been the administrations most vocal advocate of 
condom use for sexually active people who are not in monogomous 
relationships 
that booklet has been distributed to an estimated 19 million 
americans many via mail from individual members of congress who 
requested copies to mail to their constituents the basic themes 
laid down in the 1986 report have been repeated in subsequent 
public health service documents 
the outspoken koops planned presence at the wednesday 
announcement was an indication the mailing will adhere to the 
approach he has been taking on aids education and prevention 
his spokesman jim brown declined to say what role koop had 
played in preparation of the mailer or whether it will state the 
surgeon generals position on condom use 
it would be really difficult to leave out the surgeon general 
who has been the voice of this administration speaking out on aids 
since he was first asked to do the 1986 report by the 
president brown said in an interview 
brown noted that dr robert windom the no 2 official in the 
health department and hhs undersecretary donald newman will be 
making a simultaneous announcement of the mailing wednesday in 
geneva at the world health organization 
we discovered when we were in london in january for an aids 
conference attended by health ministers from almost every country 
in the world that there was a great deal of concern about what the 
united states was doing brown said we thought this was a good 
opportunity to show them what were doing now in addition to all 
the things we have done before 
</TEXT>
