appeal of a 1986 ruling overturning a referendum in dearborn in 
november 1985 the voters in the town located on detroits western 
border had approved a measure that would ban nonresidents from 35 
of its 37 parks 
the american civil liberties union challenged the law saying it 
effectively discriminated against blacks from neighboring detroit 
william saxton representing dearborn said tuesday that the 
ruling should be overturned because the same argument could be used 
to strike down a number of other laws that had potential 
discriminatory effects 
the plaintiffs are making an abhorrent argument he said 
in an interview outside the hearing the city has a right to 
control its own possessions 
but wayne state university law professor robert sedler who 
argued in behalf of the aclu said the ordinance is going to make 
the dearborn parks all white 
however he added the case is limited and should apply only to 
dearborn parks 
our view is a very narrow one he said 
in september 1986 wayne county circuit judge marvin stempien 
ruled that the ban was unconstitutional because of its possible 
discriminatory effect and its proposed random checks of park users 
for identity documents 
