leftist guerrillas on tuesday 
imposed a nationwide road transport ban that forced workers to walk 
to their jobs or pay high fares to truck drivers 
the ban the third this year reduced traffic on intercity roads 
and highways by up to 90 percent according to several dispatchers 
and broadcast reports from the provinces city traffic appeared to 
be about a third of that on a normal day 
only two privately owned city buses were seen in a tour of the 
capital and the surrounding area several stateowned buses with 
soldiers aboard for protection were providing transport as were 
some army trucks 
but most salvadorans either walked or boarded overcrowded 
pickups and vans converted to public transport by their owners the 
drivers charged an average of two colones 40 cents per trip or 
about six times the average bus fare 
guerrillas of the farabundo marti national liberation front who 
have waged an 8year campaign against the usbacked government 
warned drivers to heed the measure they did not say how long it 
would last 
