<TEXT>
scientists have identified details of a 
key part of a gene responsible for male sexual development a step 
that could eventually help doctors treat prostate cancer and 
diagnose infertility in men 
the gene allows body cells to create surface structures called 
receptors to which male sex hormones attach themselves 
that binding triggers sexrelated functions in the cells said 
frank french head of the laboratories of reproductive biology at 
the university of north carolina at chapel hill 
its like a switch french said when the switch is turned 
on it causes genes to stimulate certain characteristic functions 
of the cell 
the work reported last month in the journal science was 
carried out by french and colleagues at the university 
the finding is a very major discovery its like getting the 
rest of the words to hamlet said donald coffey director of 
research at the brady urological institute at johns hopkins 
hospital in baltimore and chairman of the national cancer 
institutes prostate cancer program 
the north carolina researchers used the information to create 
special proteins called antibodies which detected the presence of 
the sex hormone receptors in laboratory animals 
a test based on these antibodies may one day help doctors choose 
proper therapy for prostate cancer french said 
the test called an androgen receptor assay would tell whether 
prostate cells still have the receptor on their surfaces the 
receptor disappears in advanced cases of prostate cancer french 
said 
once the receptor is gone hormone therapy to fight inoperable 
prostate cancer would be useless said coffey 
well know not to waste time with hormone therapy if its not 
going to work coffey said 
prostate cancer is the second leading cause of cancer death in 
men an estimated 96000 men get it each year in the united states 
and 27000 die from it according to the national cancer institute 
the receptor test also may ultimately prove helpful in 
determining the cause of infertility in some men french said 
without the receptor a man would appear female because his 
cells would not respond to male sex hormone french said however 
in some men the receptor is present but its binding ability is 
impaired resulting in normal development but infertility 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

