said he believed a huge percentage of the soviet unions two 
million jews would emigrate if given the chance 
most have not applied knowing they would be subject to 
discrimination in employment and other opportunities during the 
long often unending period while waiting for approval 
schifter said however it looks as if a good many people 
could get their cases processed reasonably fast if they were to 
apply right now theyre afraid and theyre afraid quite rightfully 
because anything can turn in the soviet union with a very short 
time and they can find themselves in great difficulty after that 
a good many of them also are not fully aware today of what the 
possibilities are that you can indeed fill out the forms get them 
filed and theres a chance within six weeks or two months perhaps 
to get your application processed he said 
schifter said soviet jews should be assured that the 
possibilities are there now and they ought to take advantage of it 
if this is what they want to do 
after reaching a high point of 51320 exit permits in 1979 
soviet emigration declined to 914 in 1986 it rebounded to 8155 in 
1987 and will go even higher this year if the monthly figures hold 
up in march for example 986 jews emigrated the highest monthly 
total since 1981 according to the conference on soviet jewry 
