<TEXT>
a congressional critic of nuclear power urged 
the nuclear regulatory commission on tuesday to reject a staff 
proposal that would permit atomic reactors to operate at low power 
without an alarm system to warn nearby residents in case of an 
emergency 
the recommendation scheduled for a preliminary commission vote 
shortly is aimed at the seabrook nh plant the atomic safety 
and licensing appeal board has blocked a lowpower license for 
seabrook because of the lack of a warning system for neighboring 
communities in nearby massachusetts 
during fuel loading and lowpower operation the potential for 
an accident still exists including the possibility of a reactor 
reaching a critical level rep edward j markey dmass said 
in a letter to nrc chairman lando w zech jr 
while the magnitude of the risk may be lower than at full 
power it is no lower than it was in 1982 when the nrc examined 
the issue in detail and adopted existing standards markey wrote 
critics say seabrook officials want to quickly secure a 
lowpower license because they fear they will lose their chance to 
operate the 54 billion plant if massachusetts gov michael s 
dukakis is elected president 
dukakis has led the fight against seabrook and his refusal to 
cooperate in emergency evacuation planning for the six bay state 
municipalities has delayed the licensing process 
its clear that theyre trying to push this through because 
they dont know what the future holds for the nrc said markey 
aide cathy hurwit 
nrc spokesman robert newlin said the commission was expected to 
vote soon on whether to make the recommendation a proposed 
rule that would be subject to a public comment period but not 
necessarily a hearing and a final commission vote newlin said 
nrc officials say the current rules do not specifically require 
an offsite warning system to obtain a lowpower license and that 
the rules change would only clarify the regulations 
but a 1982 commission explanation of the rule does specify 
an offsite system and that clearly has been the interpretation of 
the licensing appeals board 
the board ruled in february that a lowpower license for 
seabrook is precluded unless and until the applicants have 
submitted substitute public notification plans for the 
massachusetts communities within the emergency zone 
seabrook has proposed an alternate alert system that would use 
truckmounted sirens backed up by sirenequipped helicopters 
according to plant spokesman rob williams 
williams said seabrook officials plan to use that system during 
lowpower operation but with the rules change would not need to 
wait for regulatory approval of the system approval would be 
needed eventually for a fullpower license 
