<TEXT>
a widow whose husband smoked and died of 
lung cancer can pursue a wrongful death lawsuit against a tobacco 
company and a retailer that sold cigarettes the minnesota court of 
appeals ruled tuesday 
a threejudge panel unanimously overturned a district court 
ruling in may 1987 that ann forsters claim was preempted by the 
federal cigarette and advertising act 
in march 1985 mrs forster and her husband john sued rj 
reynolds co manufacturers of camel cigarettes and erickson 
petroleum corp owner of holiday station stores the forsters 
claimed the retailer sold forster the cigarettes 
forster who was diagnosed as having inoperable lung cancer in 
november 1984 died of the disease in june 1985 and the suit 
originally filed as a product liability case was amended to a 
wrongful death action the lawsuit alleges that cigarettes caused 
the lung cancer 
judge thomas kalitowski who wrote the majority opinion said 
the us supreme court historically has taken a narrow view of 
federal preemption 
in overturning the lower court kalitowski said our holding 
is founded on the strong presumption basic to our system of 
federalism that state police powers are not superseded by federal 
actions without clear and unmistakable congressional intent or 
absolute necessity 
we recognize appellants claims may be difficult to prove 
the ruling said however the difficulty of proof should not 
preclude the basic right to present claims 
