<TEXT>
a man convicted of murdering seven women and 
letting their bodies rot faces life in prison rather than death 
under an unusual sentence handed down tuesday 
common pleas judge robert a latrone issued six death sentences 
against harrison marty graham but ordered him first to serve up 
to 14 years in prison on seven counts of abuse of a corpse and life 
in prison for the remaining murder 
latrone who ordered the sentences to run consecutively 
explained that he chose life in prison over the death penalty on 
the first murder count because of a mitigating circumstance the 
lack of a previous record but the conviction on the first count 
legally qualified as an aggravating circumstance on the second 
through seventh murder counts necessitating the death penalty in 
those six cases 
graham could not apply for parole during the life sentence 
however without putting the death sentence into effect defense 
attorney joel moldovsky said 
graham whose attorney said he was mentally retarded sat 
motionlessly through the sentencing a halfsmoked cigarette tucked 
behind his ear 
moldovsky called the sentence unusually compassionate and 
brilliant 
but assistant district attorney roger king who characterized 
graham as a serial killer during the trial questioned the 
legality of the order 
it would appear that the greater sentence would come first 
he said meaning the death penalty 
the pennsylvania supreme court reviews all death sentences 
last week latrone convicted graham of seven counts of murder 
and abuse of a corpse graham waived his right to a jury trial 
leaving the decisions including sentencing solely to the judge 
police found the bodies of seven women in august 1987 after 
graham was evicted from his apartment because of a putrid stench 
officers found six rotting bodies in grahams bedroom leg and foot 
bones outside his apartment and a torso in a neighboring houses 
basement 
at his mothers urging graham surrendered to police a week 
after the bodies were discovered 
in a statement his lawyer unsuccessfully contested graham told 
police he strangled the women while having sex and after feeding 
them drugs and alcohol he said that when the bodies began piling 
up in his apartment he began experiencing trouble with furball 
bugs or maggots and with birds feeding on the remains outside 
the window 
the 28yearold graham did not testify during the sixweek trial 
moldovsky who had argued his client did not know right from 
wrong and might have killed the women accidentally or because of 
drug or alcohol use said he would consult with grahams family 
before deciding whether to appeal 
