beyond that history gets complicated you can no longer 
simplify it in quite this way 
the shows historical adviser janet meisel disagreed a 
medievalist would say the further back you go the more complicated 
history gets 
she said the complications make history interesting 
we are lulled by similarities in thinking ah yes they 
historical figures are just like us but they really werent 
said meisel wrapped in a scarf and a winter coat against the 
coastal chill 
the past is not like the present thats what makes it a 
useful intellectual exercise 
on sabbatical from the university of texas at austin where she 
is a professor of medieval history meisel said she approved of the 
shows efforts to make history accessible 
i know there are some historians who really object to the 
idea she said but i guess my feeling is that history is so 
badly taught as long as we have the football coach or the 
basketball coach whichever one isnt teaching english teach 
history id like to see history that looks right and is right and 
entertaining 
meisel said her task was to verify matters ranging from 
historical methodology to horns 
did vikings remove the horns on cattle or not she said 
we have this pseudoviking from a university whose particular 
field is agricultural animals in the middle ages whos saying you 
cannot have loppedoff horns 
but i can show you anglosaxon laws where people were in fact 
required to lop off the horns of cattle so you do not gore your 
neighbors or your neighbors cattle 
for locals such as blacksmith david daley timeline is an 
opportunity to recreate his reallife profession onscreen 
its good fun the island could do with something like this to 
put it on the map the 42yearold daley said 
his wife gillian has a bit part in the show as well playing 
what daley described as a lusty maiden or something 
coproducer gary witt had nothing but praise for his cast 
were smearing mud on their costumes and theyre letting us 
do it god love em he said 
