<TEXT>
the federal government has filed a lawsuit 
against first national bank of chicago charging the bank with 
discriminating against men and women through various features of 
its pension plan 
the lawsuit filed monday by the equal employment opportunity 
commission asks that first national change its pension plans and 
pay monetary damages to employees 
no specific damages were mentioned in the lawsuit but eeoc 
spokesman john rowe said the amount would be very substantial 
the lawsuit involves one claim of discrimination against men and 
two against women 
the claim of discrimination against men is based on a provision 
in the pension plans that calculates pension amounts for each 
employee at retirement using a percentage of that persons earnings 
rowe said the men are credited with a lower percentage than 
women for employment before 1965 
the commission claims that the bank in 1970 in an effort to 
correct the problem lowered womens pension benefits to be equal 
to those of men a move the eeoc says is illegal 
a third claim involves the use of sexbased mortality tables for 
calculating pension benefits the commission said such tables 
result in lower monthly benefits for women because women retirees 
on average live longer than men 
rowe said the bank stopped using the sexbased mortality tables 
about four years ago but didnt change its practices for prior 
periods of employment 
</TEXT>
