<DOCNO> AP880503-0254 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it looked like the movie wall 
street brokers wearing yellow yuppie ties waving id tags 
and shouting into walkietalkies jostled one another to make bids 
on the floor of the rio stock exchange 
but the object of the bidding was not stocks bonds commodities 
or precious metals it was part of brazils mountainous foreign 
debt of 121 billion 
thoughout latin america which as a whole owes the rest of the 
world 410 billion and has been unable to pay it back socalled 
debtforequity swaps are being tried as a way to break the 
impasse 
not everyone is enthusiastic about the idea which involves 
trading big debts for generally smaller amounts of equity in local 
enterprises 
some countries say the swaps cause inflation and lead to 
foreign domination of their economies some major creditor 
banks mostly us ones which sank billions into latin loans say 
the swaps force them to cancel their debt at too hefty a discount 
on the other hand many small banks in europe japan the 
middle east and american cities such as cleveland pittsburgh and 
dallas see the swaps as a way to salvage at least some of the 
money they sunk into the region in the 1970s 
swaps will never be a total solution to the debt crisis but 
they certainly are a step in the right direction said maarten l 
pronk the rio representative of hollands nmb bank currently the 
worlds no 1 middleman in debtforequity trades there are 
pluses and minuses on both sides but the overall result is very 
interesting 
in brazil which has just begun monthly debt auctions equity 
trades could reduce the countrys foreign debt by as much as 4 
billion this year officials estimate 
in a typical transaction a company hoping to start or expand a 
brazilian business purchases a certain amount of the countrys debt 
from a creditor bankat a steep discount and then brings that debt 
to market to bid against other companies on a repayment plan from 
the central bank of brazil 
successful bidders the ones who accept the biggest discounts 
from the central bank get repaid in local currency which is to 
be invested in their local enterprises the benefit to the 
companies comes in the difference between what they paid for the 
debt and what the central bank agrees to repay them for example a 
company might purchase debt at 50 cents on the dollar and then win 
a bid of 70 cents on the dollar from the central bank in the 
auction 
the government regulates the auctions screens the types of 
projects to be funded and sets quotas on the amount of debt it will 
repay while the process helps ease the national debt burden the 
regulations are designed to control the inflationary effects of the 
swaps which infuse the economy with fresh capital and increase the 
money in circulation 
brazil like most other countries also protects its end of the 
deal by requiring investors to keep their assets in the country for 
a period of years 
the rio debt auction was a complete success sergio 
barcellos the president of the rio stock exchange said in an 
interview 
another aggressive debt swapper is chile which still owes an 
estimated 217 billion but has traded off 3 billion worth 
thanks to such deals us australian new zealand and middle 
eastern private interests have bought into chilean mining 
companies private pension funds fruitgrowing firms and fishing 
companies 
some critics complain that encouraging foreign interests to swap 
debt for equity could lead to a denationalization of the latin 
american economy but in chile the authoritarian regime of 
president gen augusto pinochet says the swaps will continue 
especially since the country is writing off debt at the rate of 59 
to 61 cents on the dollar 
mexico the no 2 third world debtor owing 105 billion swapped 
some 2 billion of debt for local assets but stopped the program 
last year when the inflation rate hit a record 1592 percent 
under the mexican swaps made at a discount of around 30 
percent nissan motor co ford motor co chrysler corp 
volkswagen american express and club med acquired or increased 
holdings in the country 
argentina third among latin debtors with 55 billion owed this 
year held two debtforequity auctions and authorized 15 specific 
debtswap deals in these projects 241 million worth of debt is 
to be canceled in exchange for 139 million worth of ownership in 
two breweries a soft drink bottling plant a beer bottling 
company an auto parts firm and a manufacturer of insulin 
but juan ciminari the secretary of industry and foreign trade 
echoed mexicos worries about inflation with argentinas inflation 
rate running over 200 percent a year the swap program could get 
tripped up he said 
small poor bolivia has succeeded in reducing its 900 million 
debt to foreign banks by swapping part of it for local assets at 
the bargainbasement rate of 11 cents on the dollar but there is 
controversy because of fear foreigners will gain control of 
traditionally staterun companies 
venezuela has gone timidly into debt swaps uruguay says it 
intends to start them colombia and paraguay havent shown much 
interest in such operations while peru which has openly refused 
to repay most of its 167 billion debt doesnt consider swaps at 
all 
also generally in the antiswap camp are the giant us banks 
that tied up billions of dollars in latin american loans citibank 
chase manhattan morgan guaranty trust and manufacturers hanover 
are in principle against huge discounts on the money owed to them 
</TEXT>
