<TEXT>
trading halted for more than 2 hours tuesday on 
the chicago mercantile exchange after water from a burst pipe 
flooded the exchanges telecommunications room disabling its 
automated price quotation system 
the chicago mercantile exchange is the leading us market for 
stockindex and livestock futures and the trading shutdown had a 
quieting effect on the nations other financial markets analysts 
said 
we dont know what caused it but it leaked a whole lot of 
water exchange spokesman andrew yemma said after trading resumed 
at 1045 am cdt 
exchange officials called the trading halt at 805 am cdt 45 
minutes after the opening of trading in foreign currency and 
treasury bill futures trading in stockindex and agricultural 
futures had not yet opened when the halt was called yemma said 
a large water pipe in the sprinkler system burst and flooded the 
secondfloor telecommunications room located just below the 
exchanges trading floor he said 
the water disabled the exchanges highspeed telephone lines 
which carry price quotes to subscribers of marketinformation 
services around the world 
the exchanges computers were not damaged so trading could have 
continued but the customers and users of the market wouldnt have 
known what the prices were yemma said 
during the trading halt stock market players were unable to 
hedge their equity investments via the chicago mercantile 
exchanges popular standard amp poors 500 futures contract that may 
have limited trading activity on the new york stock exchange 
analysts said 
youre definitely not going to see anybody make a big play 
without the futures open said arthur liming an analyst with lns 
financial group in chicago 
while the merc was down he said there was one or two things 
less to watch on what was a quiet day to begin with 
yemma said it was impossible to calculate the dollar value of 
the loss of volume at the chicago mercantile exchange 
chicagos midamerica commodity exchange which trades smaller 
versions of the most popular futures contracts offered by other 
exchanges may have benefited from the mercs problems however 
spokesman william murschel said the midam halted trading in its 
stockindex livestock foreign currency and treasury bill futures 
at the same time as the mercantile exchange then resumed trading 
in those contracts at 10 am cdt when it appeared the merc might 
be closed for a day or more 
when the midam reopened it really became the marketplace for 
those contracts that were affected by the cme so there was an 
alternative marketplace available murschel said it was the 
midams day in the sun 
</TEXT>
