<TEXT>
eastman kodak cos earnings rose 46 
percent in the first quarter of 1988 to 260 million from 178 
million a year ago the company said tuesday 
the photographic giant said the increase was due to increases in 
sales volume the weak dollar and earnings from sterling drug 
inc which kodak acquired in february 
on a per share basis kodak earned 80 cents in the first three 
months of the year compared to 53 cents during the first quarter 
of 1987 
sales increased 25 percent to 333 billion from 265 billion 
last year 
analysts said the results were better than expected 
the only surprise in the report was a 2 percent earnings drop in 
the companys imaging segment which includes photography and 
copiers according to charles ryan of merrill lynch amp co in new 
york 
ryan said the decline was due to repackaging of certain film 
products and increased advertising expenses 
he said however the expenditures would pay off later 
another analyst eugene glazer of dean witter reynolds inc in 
new york said a large portion of the per share earnings increase 
27 cents was due to the declining value of the dollar which makes 
foreign profits worth more in dollar terms 
glazer said it was a low quality source of earnings gain 
he said the sale of assets in france resulted in another 4 cents 
of the pershare gain 
both analysts noted strong gains in the companys chemicals 
segment and the sterling drug subsidiary 
sales rose in each of kodaks three segments sales in its 
imaging segment were 2 billion up from 18 billion last year 
chemical sales were 654 million up from 588 million and sales 
in health products were 640 million up from 274 million 
sales outside the united states were healthy up 23 percent in 
the imaging segment up 16 percent in chemicals and up 104 percent 
in health 
</TEXT>
