staley continental inc announced 
tuesday its board rejected a sweetened 142 billion takeover bid 
from british sugar producer tate amp lyle plc and may consider other 
offers 
staley chairman donald e nordlund said several unidentified 
third parties are interested in acquiring the company based in 
this northwest chicago suburb 
the company is continuing discussions with certain third 
parties and expects to enter into negotiations nordlund said in 
a statement issued by the company 
in new york stock exchange trading tuesday staley shares 
advanced 50 cents to 38375 
staleys board recommended that the companys stockholders 
reject the 35ashare bid which was made last week and approved 
tuesday by tate amp lyle shareholders meeting in london 
when it first moved to take over staley last month the british 
company offered 32 per share of common stock 
staley the united states secondlarged refiner of corn 
sweeteners behind decaturbased archer daniels midland co urged 
its stockholders april 21 to reject the first offer 
in its statement tuesday staley said its financial advisers 
first boston corp and merrill lynch capital markets had 
concluded the revised tate offer was inadequate 
staleys board did not make a recommendation on tates offers of 
5315 a share for depositary preferred stock or 105 a share for 
cumulative preference stock 
but the companys statement noted the british companys takeover 
bid was conditioned on receiving a minimum number of commonstock 
shares and that staleys board has recommended rejecting the common 
stock bid 
in a related matter staleys board extended its poison pill 
antitakeover defense until may 10 at 5 pm tates revised bid 
expires at midnight edt on that date 
spokesmen for the companies did not return telephone messages 
tuesday seeking comment but industry analysts have said staley has 
a fair market value of about 40 a share 
after tates first offer clinton mayer iii an analyst in new 
york with bear stearns inc said that if he were a staley 
stockholder he probably wouldnt sell for less than 40 
tate amp lyle owns about 5 percent of staleys stock and wants to 
acquire the entire company for its ae staley manufacturing co 
subsidiary which produces corn sweeteners 
staley was based in decatur ill until about three years ago 
when it moved its headquarters to rolling meadows the british 
company has promised to move staleys headquarters back to the 
central illinois city if its takeover succeeds 
staley continental also owns cfs continental inc a leading 
foodservice supplier 
