<TEXT>
eastern airlines has asked a federal judge to 
clarify his order barring the financially troubled carrier from 
selling its northeast shuttle service to another subsidiary of its 
parent texas air corp 
meanwhile the federal aviation administration is investigating 
machinist union charges that the miamibased carrier is guessing 
the weight of cargo aboard its aircraft 
weve been looking into the allegations for about a week and a 
half faa spokesman roger myers said tuesday we have not found 
any irregularities yet 
the faa has already fined eastern 823500 for safety violations 
and is conducting an inspection of its fleet 
eastern spokesman robin matell said the airline is absolutely 
safe in all phases of its operations and accused the machinists 
of using safety issues as a smokescreen to obscure economic issues 
in contract negotiations 
in washington the motion by eastern which was filed last week 
under seal in us district court appears to have been made in an 
attempt to ensure that a planned business transaction would not 
violate a series of orders issued by district judge john h pratt 
in march pratt held eastern in contempt of a july 2 1987 
order issued in a labor dispute for taking steps to sell the 
eastern air shuttle to a newly created subsidiary of texas air 
corp for 225 million the service operates between new york and 
washington and new york and boston 
pratt barred eastern from taking any further steps to sell the 
shuttle ruling the transaction would violate the status quo in 
working conditions he had ordered last summer 
the proposed sale was opposed by the machinists union which 
charged the company was trying to undermine the unions ability to 
represent shuttle employees by transferring the operation to 
another subsidiary 
matell refused to comment tuesday on why the airlines filed the 
motion saying only the entire letter is under seal and we do 
not care to clarify 
court documents requesting that the clarification motion be 
placed under seal said eastern was trying to protect confidential 
and proprietary information about its business plans 
eastern would be placed at a serious and irreparable 
competitive disadvantage if the information contained in the motion 
and memorandum and supporting affidavits is made public the 
companys deputy general counsel michael j smith said in a sworn 
affidavit 
disclosure of the information could impair easterns ability 
to manage its operations and to resolve its financial 
difficulties 
in a reply to easterns request attorneys for the machinists 
said the union did not agree with the airlines interpretation of 
pratts order 
the us circuit court of appeals here is scheduled to hear 
arguments thursday on easterns appeal of pratts order barring the 
shuttle sale 
